1S pass 3S pass 4S pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "7b18ffc4410cff2fe0bbe7914420a703fc3c1028e080b2b81593f8f582c7168f"]
[Category "Defense"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "defense/defensive_signals"]
[Student "W"]
{[showcards W:HA E:HQ S:H5 N:H6]

You are South. The bidding has been as shown. You led the \HA, North puts on the \HQ. It's your play. 

Play the \H2.

North's \HQ is either a singleton, (practically impossible), or a signal showing that he also holds the \HJ. In either case you can reach the North hand on the second trick by playing a low \H. Since you don't particularly want to start playing \Ds from your side, you go ahead and play a small \H, won by North with the \HJ.

North next plays the \DQ and however East tries it your side will take the next two \D tricks and set the contract.}
[Play "W"]HA

